### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

common, platform-server

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

when a module is lazy loaded, and a component subscribes to a httpClient.get() to set a variable that fulfills the condition to render a child component, it seems that the child component never rendered in the server.

consider the following sitiuation:

1- appModule contains a router to load `feature.module` lazely when the path matches 'lazy', and in its turn it loads the component `lazy.component`

```
// app.module

const routes=[
  {
    path: 'lazy',
    loadChildren: () =>
      import('./feature/feature.module').then(
        (modules) => modules.FeatureModule
      ),
  },
]
```
```
// feature.module
const routes: Routes = [{ path: '**', component: LazyComponent }];
```
2- now `lazy.component` should be loaded when we go to the path `/lazy`
```
// lazy.component
@component(
    template: '<lazy-child-comp *ngIf="ready"></lazy-child-comp>',
}
export class LazyComponent {
  ready=false
  constructor(private httpClient:HttpClient) {
     this.httpClient.get('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/todos/1').subscribe(()=>{
       this.ready=true
     })
  }
}
```
lazy.component` performs an http request, and when it is completed it set `this.ready=true` so `<lazy-child-comp>` starts to be rendered

when `<lazy-child-comp>` renderes it log `'===> lazy-child: constructor'` to the console.
this logs to the browser's console, but doesn't log to the server's console


**tests**
- the exactly same sinario is made with `normal.component` when you go to the path `/normal` and it works in both browser and server sides.
- when you replace `http.get()` with `of('')` to simulate an Observable, it works with `lazy.component` in both browser and server sides, even when you pipe `delay(1000)` to it.

